FieldRequiredTypeDescriptionExample user_promptTrueDYNAMIC_STRINGMain instructions or question for the LLM. Supports variable substitution using double-brace placeholders that reference connected nodes via context_data. Can be multiline; should clearly describe the task and any formatting requirements.Summarize the following support ticket in 3 bullet points:

{{TicketText.output}} modelTrueCOMBOLLM model to use. Options are loaded from the Salt LLM service and grouped by provider. You select by human-friendly name; the node resolves it to the provider model ID internally.anthropic/claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022 max_tokensTrueINTMaximum number of tokens the model may generate. Range 0 to 128000. Larger values allow longer answers but increase latency and cost; typical values are 256–4096.2048 system_promptFalseDYNAMIC_STRINGHigh-level instructions defining the assistant’s role, rules, and tone. If empty, a default system prompt is used. Supports variable substitution using values from context_data.You are a senior support analyst. Write concise, neutral summaries suitable for an internal CRM system. temperatureFalseFLOATControls randomness of outputs. Range 0 to 2, default 0.7. Lower values make responses more deterministic; higher values make them more diverse and creative.0.5 context_dataFalse*Multi-connect input for upstream data. Each connected node’s output is collected into a context object whose fields can be referenced in prompts with patterns like {{NodeName.output}}. Used only for prompt variable substitution, not sent as a separate field to the LLM API.Connected nodes such as FetchCustomerProfile.output and LoadConversationHistory.output, then used in the prompt as {{FetchCustomerProfile.output}}. top_pFalseFLOATNucleus sampling parameter (0 to 1). When set, the model samples from the smallest token set whose cumulative probability exceeds this value. Not all providers use it; leaving it null uses provider defaults.0.9 top_kFalseINTLimits sampling to the top K most probable tokens. Range 1 to 500. Only supported by some providers; ignored where unsupported.40 frequency_penaltyFalseFLOATPenalty applied to tokens in proportion to how often they have already appeared, to reduce repetition. Range -2 to 2; small positive values help avoid repetitive wording.0.3 presence_penaltyFalseFLOATPenalty that encourages the model to introduce new topics instead of staying on the same one. Range -2 to 2; positive values increase topical diversity.0.2 json_modeFalseBOOLEANWhen true, the node configures the call for structured JSON only and strongly instructs the model to respond with valid JSON and no extra text. Enables provider-native response_format handling.True response_schemaFalseSTRINGJSON schema (or schema-like object) that describes the desired output shape. Used only when json_mode is true. Injected into the system prompt and used for optional local validation.{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "summary": {"type": "string"},
    "sentiment": {"type": "string", "enum": ["positive", "neutral", "negative"]}
  },
  "required": ["summary", "sentiment"]
} fallback_modelFalseCOMBOOptional backup model to try automatically if the primary model fails. Uses the same option set as model. If unset or equal to model, no fallback attempt is made.openai/gpt-4o

FieldTypeDescriptionExample responseSTRINGThe LLM’s primary output. In normal mode this is free-form text. In json_mode with response_schema it is a JSON string that has had any markdown fences removed and may have been validated against the schema.{
  "summary": "The customer cannot log into their account due to a password reset loop.",
  "sentiment": "negative"
} errorSTRINGError message when execution fails. Typically empty on success. When both primary and fallback models fail, the node raises an execution error rather than silently returning an empty response.LLM call failed: provider_timeout: upstream model did not respond within 30s; fallback model also failed: rate_limit_exceeded
